The Book of  JOB, Variants (CATSS Project)

 

From bdunning Wed Jan 11 11:26:37 1995

GRenberg, Summer ’96 [needs final checking]

 

Trouble spots, difficult variants, parts that should be checked, etc., are denoted by boldface throughout.

 

There are three types of apostrophes/single-quotes used in the app.crit.  These are the characters I am using to represent them:

                ’ or ‘       (Single-quote mark, will become ' once file is converted to text format)

                                Represents the most common of the three, the straight quote mark that tilts slightly

                                forwards, used for witnesses such as 534' and 46'

                `               (Key in upper right of keyboard, under tilde)

                                Represents the straight quote mark that tilts slightly backwards, as in L’`

                !               Represents the rounded single-quote, as in L’ and <it>lI</>’

 

Look (Ctrl-F) for each #-sign.  I’m not sure what they mean or how to handle them.  And, to be honest, they’ve gotten on my nerves!

  #13 indicates hexaplaric asterisk (Theodotionic text)

Look at each occurrence of “cf” because sometimes when dealing with a variant that has “cf” it might not be necessary to use “cf” for each addition and deletion in that variant.

 

Another possible problem is witnesses such as <it>C</>{1-147}, which is how it appears in the app.crit.  <it>C</> includes 147 as a manuscript, so I have done it:  <it>C</>{1}{-147}.  If this isn’t right, it needs to be changed throughout for C{1}, C{2} and C{3}.  [seems to mean first hand of  italic C, but if that is a family not a MS, then what?]

 

What is (2{o}), as in “Ol  (2{o})”?  And (1{o})? [2nd occurrence of that word in the verse]
